Option 2: Method 4 (Dynamic Registration) – Advanced Automation
Step-by-Step Setup
1. Auto-Prefix Admin Controllers
typescript

// src/admin/admin.module.ts
import { Module, Controller } from '@nestjs/common';
import { UsersController } from './users/users.controller';
import { ProductsController } from './products/products.controller';

const adminControllers = [UsersController, ProductsController];

@Module({
  controllers: adminControllers,
  providers: [{
    provide: 'ADMIN_PREFIX',
    useValue: 'admin', // Centralized prefix
  }],
})
export class AdminModule {
  static register() {
    return {
      module: AdminModule,
      // Dynamically prepend 'admin/' to all paths
      controllers: adminControllers.map(controller => ({
        ...controller,
        path: `admin/${controller.path}`,
      })),
    };
  }
}

2. Update Controllers (Optional)
typescript

// src/admin/users/users.controller.ts
@Controller() // Path will be set dynamically
export class UsersController {
  @Get('users') // Final route: `GET /admin/users`
  getUsers() { return 'Users'; }
}

3. Register in AppModule
typescript

// src/app.module.ts
@Module({
  imports: [AdminModule.register(), ClientModule],
})
export class AppModule {}

Key Differences
Method	Pros	Cons
RouterModule	Explicit, NestJS-native	Slightly verbose setup
Dynamic Registration	Fully automated	Complex, less readable
Recommendation

    Use RouterModule (Method 2) if you prefer:

        Clear visibility of route mappings.

        Native NestJS support.

    Use Dynamic Registration (Method 4) if you:

        Need to scale with many admin controllers.

        Prefer convention-over-configuration.

